\subsubsection{\textbf{Pressure radial and tangential pressures }}

In summary, for $\alpha>0$ we can see that the energy density is always greater than zero, while the radial pressure is less than zero, both vanish when $r$ goes to infinity. 

On the other hand, the lateral pressures are less than zero for $r<r_1$, become positive for $r>r_1$ reaching a maximum at $r_2$ and then decrease until vanish when $r$ goes to infinity.

The solution may be a naked singularity $(\mu <l^{4})$ or a black hole $(\mu >l^{4})$. In case of a black hole there is an event horizon at $r=r_{0}$, which can hide the zone of negative tangential pressures ($\mu >\mu _{1}$) or otherwise, leave it uncovered.



